Redi-Data, a division of Redi-Direct, is a list provider specializing in healthcare data.  Redi-Data receives, enhances, and processes data for Physician, Nurse, Pharmacists, Dentists, Physician Assistants and Nurse Practitioners.  We specialize in both postal and email lists with an in-house mail shop and email deployment services.  Each month we process over 200 million postal records and deploy millions of emails for our customers.  

As Director of Data Services, I oversee all incoming data, and the procedures around the processing of that data.  Procedures include: Postal Process of all files through BCC Postal software, deceased processing, validation of data and consolidation of duplicate records.  Redi-Data compiles email addresses from many sources which all must be validated and matched to our base files.  These sources come at different times including daily data from our deployment services.  As the hands-on Director, I lead a team in the development and executing of these processing.

As Director of Web Applications, I design, built and support web systems which allow users to select the segment of data they want to market to.  For Redi-Data email marketing services we maintain multiple deployment systems, domains, and IP addresses.  A key element of my job involves these systems ensuring they are setup correctly and healthy to produce the best response and delivery rates.  The team I oversee included web programmers in NJ and India.  In NJ the team includes customer service employees specialized in postal and email campaigns.

Being Director of Web Applications and Data Services keeps me involved in the full cycle of our work from incoming data, applications, deployments, technical sales support, and customer service. The execution and operations of these area has direct impact on the company revenue.  Working for 15 years for Redi-Direct family of companies has been a source of pride and accomplishment for me.

column29:
See: OpenFIGI.com for more information on the FIGI standard and data.

Our industry for too long lacked single open standards that would identify Entities and Instruments.  I wrote about this in 2001 after convening an industry working group to address Unique Security Identification, and that paper is still referenced today throughout the industry in its original form.  

In September 2014, the Object Management Group (www.omg.org) officially accepted FIGI as a global  open standard. In 2021, FIGI became a US National Standard, accredited by ANSI/X9.

The Financial Instrument Global Identifier (FIGI; \'fig - ē\) provides an open, unique, non changing identifier for instrument (product/asset/security, etc) identification.

It took the 2008 credit crisis to make any movement on LEI.  But, with the creation of the LEI (Legal Entity Identifier), half of this problem was addressed.  With the creation of the FIGI, the second half of the equation is finally provided.

I am working towards educating the industry on how FIGI can help individual firms, and the industry as a whole, enable better data management and quality, improve communication with and between organizations, reduce costs and improve the information we use for critical decision making.

Instrument identification has been a hap-hazard collection of schemes that fit a specific functional need or purpose.  Depending on where you are in the trade process, what you are doing, decisions you have to make, or who you need to communicate with, will influence what scheme (or schemes) may be appropriate.  And even then, it may not be readily apparent, there are challenges of open versus closed 'standards', redistribution and 'ownership' questions.  

Let us show you how properly leveraging the FIGI can cut through these issues and let you get back to focusing on using your data to work for your business - not trying to figure out how to get data to work.

Forbes, one of the most iconic media companies in the world, and the team behind YEC, a world-class entrepreneurship organization, have partnered to create a new kind of professional community — Forbes Councils.

Our team spent years talking to top professionals about what was working, and what was broken, in their business relationships and communities. What we found was an industry in need of a major update — one stuck in the trading-business-cards age of networking, offering little more than superficial relationships and benefits.

So we set out to create something different. Leaning on YEC’s deep understanding of community building and Forbes’ global reach and resources, we’ve created a space for exceptional business owners and leaders to come together with the people and resources that can help them thrive.

Through our selection process, we recruit and invite members not just on the basis of career success, but on their diversity of perspective and willingness to give as much as they gain. ULTRADE is the world's first Whitelabel, brandable DeFi-as-a-Service (DaaS) trading platform.
We enable Web3 audience owners to instantly launch a full-featured branded DeFi trading platform with a shared liquidity network. The only DeFi platform with true network effects built-in by design.

We are unlocking the monetization of trading for all Web3 brands with an existing audience. It disrupts the status quo where brands with a Web3 user base have no alternative but to send their users elsewhere when they need trading services.

Trading services are no longer differentiated. They are generic. From Binance or FTX, to the last exchange in a list of hundreds - trading services are practically the same. Uniswap/Sushiswap/"WhateverSwap", almost all the same.
Web3 brands, collectively, have millions of users who need these generic trading services, either for general trading or to trade the specific token of brands they use. Yet these brands cannot provide such basic trading services, as it requires sophisticated DeFi technologies. It is not their focus or competency to build them. This is what ULTRADE does. It provides the solution for all Web3 brands to spin up an entire DeFi trading platform in minutes, with full branding, enabling them to provide value-add trading services to their users without worrying about the tech. And of course collecting the fees generated under a rev-share with ULTRADE.
And liquidity? It’s all shared. Every whitelabel partner’s users are trading with all the users in the network, with the same shared liquidity. Brands do not need to jumpstart liquidity themselves.
